# MDM vs Model Registry: Managing Records or Managing Their Meaning?

Master data projects often begin with an apparently simple objective:

> Create one trusted version of the customer, supplier, material or product.

That objective leads naturally to Master Data Management.

An MDM platform can consolidate records from different systems, identify duplicates, apply business rules, route changes through approval workflows and distribute trusted master data to consuming applications.

This is necessary work.

But it does not solve every problem surrounding master data.

A company may have a governed supplier record and still be unable to explain why a particular field is mandatory in one country, which legacy source should populate it during migration, which transformation is approved or which interfaces will be affected when its definition changes.

The master record can be controlled while the model around it remains fragmented.

This is the distinction between MDM and a model registry.

MDM manages the trusted records used by the business.

A model registry manages the definitions, mappings, rules, evidence and dependencies that explain how those records are understood and changed.

The two systems are related. They are not interchangeable.

For managers, the practical question is not which category sounds more strategic.

It is:

> Are we trying to govern operational master data, or are we trying to govern the knowledge required to define, migrate and change that data?

In a complex programme, the answer may be both.

## What MDM is designed to control

Master Data Management addresses a real enterprise problem.

Customer, supplier, product and other important records are often created in several applications. Different business units maintain overlapping versions. Names, identifiers, classifications and addresses diverge. Duplicate records appear. One application contains newer information than another.

Without control, the company no longer has a dependable reference for its most important entities.

An MDM programme attempts to establish that reference.

Depending on the architecture, it may:

- consolidate data from multiple systems;
- match possible duplicate records;
- merge or link related records;
- establish a golden record;
- validate values against business rules;
- route creation and changes through workflows;
- assign stewardship responsibilities;
- maintain an audit trail;
- distribute trusted data to consuming systems.

SAP currently describes SAP Master Data Governance as a central MDM and governance hub. Its stated capabilities include golden-record creation, profiling, matching, merging, workflow-based change requests, data-quality monitoring, mass changes and auditable master-data processes. оИАciteоИВturn116601view0оИБ

This is not merely documentation.

MDM participates in the operational life of the data.

A supplier is created.

A customer address is changed.

A product classification is approved.

A duplicate is merged.

A governed value is distributed.

The platform helps determine which record the organisation should use.

## What a model registry is designed to control

A model registry begins with a different problem.

It does not ask:

> Which supplier record is the trusted one?

It asks:

> What is the approved definition of a supplier, how should its attributes be populated, and what depends on those definitions?

The registry may describe:

- business objects;
- attributes;
- source and target fields;
- source-to-target mappings;
- transformations;
- validation rules;
- conditional requirements;
- datasets;
- interfaces;
- ownership;
- decisions;
- evidence;
- exceptions;
- dependencies;
- proposed changes.

Its primary object is not the supplier record.

Its primary object is the model used to understand and manage supplier data.

That distinction can sound theoretical until a project encounters a real change.

## A practical example: changing supplier payment terms

Consider an organisation implementing SAP S/4HANA while introducing central supplier governance.

The company has several legacy systems.

Each system contains supplier payment terms, but the codes are not consistent.

One system uses `30D`.

Another uses `N30`.

A third contains local codes that combine the payment period with a baseline-date rule.

The project decides to harmonise these values into a controlled SAP payment-term set.

At first glance, this appears to be an MDM problem.

The target supplier records need governed payment terms. Changes should be approved. Invalid values should not enter the system.

An MDM platform can support that.

It can restrict users to approved payment-term values, apply workflow and maintain the final supplier records.

But the migration programme still has another set of questions:

- Which legacy codes correspond to which target payment terms?
- Does `30D` mean the same thing in every source system?
- Which supplier populations use local exceptions?
- What source fields are required to distinguish those exceptions?
- Which mapping decision has been approved?
- Which migration datasets contain the necessary information?
- Which validation rules should reject ambiguous records?
- Which purchasing organisations are affected?
- Which interfaces and reports consume the resulting value?
- What must be retested if the mapping changes?

The MDM platform governs the resulting payment term on the supplier record.

The model registry governs the reasoning and dependencies that produce that value.

Now suppose testing reveals that `30D` has two different meanings.

The project changes the mapping for one business unit.

The MDM platform can accept and govern the corrected target records.

But something must still ensure that the change is also reflected in:

- the migration mapping;
- the transformation logic;
- the reconciliation rule;
- the dataset requirements;
- the country exception;
- the interface specification;
- the test evidence;
- the decision history.

That is model governance.

Without it, the target records may eventually be corrected while the project continues to carry contradictory definitions.

## Records and definitions fail differently

The difference between the two system classes becomes clearer when we look at failure modes.

An MDM failure often appears as a record problem:

- duplicate customers;
- invalid supplier classifications;
- inconsistent product descriptions;
- missing approval;
- uncontrolled changes;
- different values across consuming systems.

A model-governance failure appears differently:

- teams use different definitions of the same attribute;
- a mapping references an obsolete source field;
- a validation rule contradicts an approved exception;
- a dataset does not contain fields expected by the target design;
- a change affects interfaces nobody reviewed;
- the reason behind a rule cannot be found;
- assumptions and approved decisions are mixed together;
- two migration waves use different mapping versions.

Both kinds of failure damage operations.

But they require different controls.

Record controls improve the quality and consistency of operational data.

Model controls improve the quality and consistency of the knowledge used to create, migrate, validate and change that data.

## Why an MDM implementation does not automatically solve migration governance

MDM is often introduced as part of an SAP transformation.

That creates an understandable expectation: once the new governance platform is implemented, the programmeвАЩs master-data problems should be under control.

The expectation is only partly correct.

MDM can govern records after the target processes and rules have been defined.

It does not automatically resolve how the programme arrives at those definitions.

Before a supplier can be governed in the target system, the project must still determine:

- which legacy suppliers should be migrated;
- how duplicates should be interpreted;
- which source fields are reliable;
- how local codes map to global codes;
- which attributes are mandatory under which conditions;
- how historical exceptions should be handled;
- which target roles and organisational levels are required;
- what evidence supports each rule.

Much of this knowledge is usually managed outside the MDM platform.

It sits in mapping workbooks, profiling reports, design documents, migration tools, Jira tickets and workshop notes.

Some of it may eventually become configuration or rules inside MDM.

Some of it remains relevant only to migration, integration or project change.

The danger is assuming that because the target record is governed, the project model is governed too.

Those are separate achievements.

## Why a model registry does not replace MDM

The opposite mistake is equally serious.

A registry can describe the approved customer or supplier model.

It can validate relationships, detect missing dataset fields, trace dependencies and control proposed model changes.

It does not therefore become an operational MDM platform.

A model registry should not be expected to:

- create productive customer or supplier records;
- perform enterprise-scale matching and merging;
- maintain golden records;
- replace stewardship workflows;
- distribute master data to operational systems;
- manage the complete lifecycle of productive master data;
- become the authoritative runtime source for business applications.

Martenweave, for example, is designed as a backend-first model governance and evidence layer. Its canonical files hold model truth; generated indexes are rebuildable; datasets can be profiled against model expectations; proposed changes pass through validation and human review. It explicitly does not position itself as a hosted MDM platform or a direct SAP write-back system. оИАfileciteоИВturn3file0оИВL9-L27оИБ оИАfileciteоИВturn3file0оИВL50-L70оИБ

This narrower role is not a weakness.

It prevents the product from duplicating systems that already handle operational master-data governance.

## The easiest way to distinguish them

Managers can use a simple test.

If the main question contains the word **record**, it probably belongs to MDM:

- Which customer record is trusted?
- Is this supplier a duplicate?
- Who may change this material?
- Has the new product been approved?
- Which value should be distributed to consuming systems?

If the main question contains the word **definition**, **mapping**, **dependency** or **evidence**, it may belong to a model registry:

- What does this customer attribute mean?
- Which source field populates it?
- Which mapping is approved?
- Why is it mandatory?
- Which dataset should contain it?
- Which rule validates it?
- Which systems depend on it?
- What evidence supports the definition?
- What will be affected if it changes?

This is not an absolute boundary.

Modern MDM products include metadata, rules, models and audit information. A registry may include some workflow and data validation.

The test remains useful because it exposes the primary purpose.

## MDM protects the operational truth

An MDM programme is concerned with the state of real business entities.

The company wants to know that:

- the supplier exists only once where appropriate;
- the customer address is current;
- the material classification is valid;
- the product hierarchy is approved;
- the record passed the required workflow;
- consuming systems received the governed version.

This is operational truth.

It directly affects procurement, sales, logistics, finance, analytics and compliance.

SAP describes MDM as the discipline of creating one trusted master reference for important business data, supported by consolidation, governance and data-quality management. оИАciteоИВturn116601view0оИБ

A model registry should respect this boundary.

It may document how the record is defined and where it is used.

It should not present itself as the system that owns the productive record unless it has actually been designed and operated for that responsibility.

## A model registry protects design truth

A migration or governance programme also needs a dependable representation of its current design.

The project needs to know:

- which objects are in scope;
- which attributes belong to them;
- how source fields correspond to target fields;
- which transformations are accepted;
- which conditions make an attribute mandatory;
- which exceptions remain valid;
- which datasets support the design;
- which decisions justify it;
- which changes are still proposals.

This is design truth.

Without it, the operational system may be configured correctly while the programme continues to work from inconsistent assumptions.

Design truth matters particularly during change.

A productive supplier record can be perfectly valid today.

Tomorrow, the company may acquire another business, add a country, replace a source system or change a regulatory rule.

The programme must then understand not only the existing values but the model that produced them.

## Data quality exists at both layers

The phrase вАЬdata qualityвАЭ is often used without specifying what is being measured.

At the record layer, data quality may mean:

- completeness;
- validity;
- uniqueness;
- consistency;
- accuracy;
- timeliness.

These are familiar MDM concerns.

At the model layer, quality has another meaning.

A model may be poor when:

- references are broken;
- field definitions conflict;
- mappings are incomplete;
- ownership is missing;
- exceptions are not represented;
- rules depend on obsolete fields;
- approved and proposed states are mixed;
- datasets cannot satisfy the expected model.

A company can therefore have clean records produced from a poorly controlled model.

It can also have a well-documented model but poor operational records because the governance process is not enforced.

Neither layer compensates fully for the other.

## Workflow is not the same as model consistency

MDM programmes often invest heavily in workflow.

That makes sense.

Master-data changes need ownership, review, segregation of duties and auditability. SAP MDG explicitly includes collaborative workflow routing, notifications and change-request processes. оИАciteоИВturn116601view0оИБ

But workflow answers a particular question:

> Did the right people approve this change?

It does not automatically answer:

> Is the change consistent with every related mapping, dataset, rule and interface?

A change may pass workflow because each approver reviewed their assigned section.

The combined model may still contain contradictions.

A model registry adds structural checks around the approval process.

For example:

- Does the proposed mapping reference a real source field?
- Is the target attribute defined?
- Does a mandatory rule conflict with an exception?
- Is the affected dataset registered?
- Which interfaces refer to the old value?
- Which dependent rules need another review?

Workflow proves that a process was followed.

Model validation helps prove that the resulting design is coherent.

Both are useful.

## Why this matters in SAP programmes

SAP master data rarely exists at one simple level.

A Business Partner can have general data, customer roles, supplier roles, addresses, tax numbers, bank details and organisational extensions.

A material may have basic data, plant data, sales data, purchasing data, accounting data and warehouse-specific attributes.

A supplier change may affect procurement, finance, compliance and integrations.

The operational master record is therefore only one part of the problem.

The programme must also manage:

- source-system representations;
- target-domain structure;
- migration-object boundaries;
- organisational dependencies;
- replication requirements;
- country-specific rules;
- interface mappings;
- ownership across functions.

MDM governs the target records and their lifecycle.

The model registry can preserve the cross-project logic that explains how all these representations connect.

This becomes especially useful when several teams are involved:

- migration;
- MDM or MDG;
- functional SAP;
- integration;
- data quality;
- business ownership;
- external implementation partners;
- AMS support.

Each team sees a different part of the same object.

The registry provides a place to connect those views without turning one teamвАЩs tool into the owner of everything.

## When MDM is enough

Not every organisation needs a separate model registry.

MDM may be sufficient when:

- the target data model is stable;
- migration complexity is low;
- few source systems are involved;
- mappings are simple and temporary;
- project knowledge is already managed reliably;
- the MDM platform contains the required rules and evidence;
- dependencies outside MDM are limited;
- changes are infrequent;
- one team owns the end-to-end model.

In this situation, adding another repository may create unnecessary operating work.

The objective is not to maximise the number of governance tools.

It is to achieve sufficient control with the smallest reasonable architecture.

## When an MDM programme still needs a model registry

The case becomes stronger when:

- several legacy systems feed the target;
- business meanings differ across regions;
- migration mappings change frequently;
- the programme includes SAP, warehouses, 3PLs or other external systems;
- datasets arrive in multiple formats and versions;
- many decisions live outside the MDM platform;
- the same attributes appear in migration, integration and reporting;
- the project relies heavily on spreadsheets;
- readiness assessments cannot be reproduced;
- AI is being used to propose mappings or rules;
- support incidents repeatedly expose missing model knowledge.

In such programmes, the registry does not compete with MDM.

It gives the programme a controlled layer around MDM.

## A sensible combined architecture

A combined approach can remain straightforward.

### The MDM or MDG platform owns

- productive master records;
- creation and change workflows;
- matching and consolidation;
- stewardship;
- business-rule enforcement;
- golden-record management;
- distribution and replication;
- operational audit history.

### The model registry owns

- project and domain definitions;
- source and target field relationships;
- migration mappings;
- dataset expectations;
- transformation logic;
- cross-system dependencies;
- decisions and evidence;
- proposed model changes;
- model validation;
- impact analysis.

### Git or another change-control mechanism records

- reviewed changes to canonical model definitions;
- comparison between model versions;
- approval evidence;
- implementation history.

### Migration and integration tools execute

- extraction;
- transformation;
- loading;
- message processing;
- reconciliation.

The boundaries do not need to be perfect.

They need to be explicit.

## What managers should ask before selecting a solution

Before buying or extending an MDM platform, ask:

- Are we trying to fix operational records or project definitions?
- Where are source-to-target mappings controlled?
- Where are migration decisions recorded?
- Can we trace a field from source evidence to target rule?
- Can we compare a current dataset with the approved model?
- Can we see the impact of changing a definition?
- Are local exceptions represented consistently?
- Does the MDM implementation cover these needs, or are we assuming it will?

Before introducing a model registry, ask:

- Which concrete gaps will it close?
- What information will become canonical?
- Who will maintain the model?
- Which reports will be generated from it?
- How will it integrate with MDM rather than duplicate it?
- Which data will deliberately remain outside it?
- Can the registry be rebuilt and validated?
- Will it reduce manual reconciliation, or merely add another documentation task?

These questions prevent category-driven architecture.

## Do not use a registry to avoid difficult MDM decisions

There is one further risk.

A project may use a model registry as a place to document disagreement without resolving it.

That is not governance.

A registry can expose that two business units define a supplier category differently.

It cannot decide which definition the enterprise should adopt.

It can show that ownership is missing.

It cannot create genuine ownership through metadata alone.

It can preserve evidence.

It cannot replace business accountability.

The system should make unresolved questions visible, assign them and prevent them from quietly appearing as approved truth.

It should not create the illusion that every problem is solved because it has been documented.

## Do not use MDM to absorb every project artefact

The reverse is also true.

An MDM implementation can become overloaded when every migration spreadsheet, technical dependency and temporary project rule is forced into the operational platform.

Not every migration artefact belongs in productive governance.

Some mappings exist only during transition.

Some source-system rules will disappear after cutover.

Some evidence is needed for audit and traceability but not for ongoing master-data maintenance.

A model registry can provide a controlled home for this information without complicating the productive MDM design.

After migration, useful parts of the model can remain as operational knowledge.

Temporary elements can be retired with an explicit history.

## The management rule

The distinction can be reduced to two statements.

**MDM answers:**

> Which master-data record should the business trust and use?

**A model registry answers:**

> Which definitions, mappings and decisions should the programme trust when creating, migrating and changing that record?

A company can need one without the other.

A large SAP transformation often needs both.

The mistake is expecting record governance to solve model governance automaticallyвАФor expecting a model repository to perform the operational work of MDM.

The strongest architecture does not make every system responsible for everything.

It gives each system a clear job.

MDM governs the record.

The model registry governs the reasoning around the record.

Migration and integration tools execute the movement.

People remain accountable for the decisions.

That separation makes the overall programme easier to understand, test and change.
